Brexit, and what's next?
NEW YORK – It will take a lot of time for Britain, Europe, and the world at large to digest the implications of the referendum on the "Brexit" led by the United Kingdom.
The most profound consequences will, of course, depend on the European Union's response to the United Kingdom's withdrawal.
Most people initially thought that the EU would not "cut off the branch it was sitting on": after all, a friendly divorce seems to be in everyone's best interest.
But the divorce – as often happens – could become complicated.
The benefits of commercial and economic integration between the United Kingdom and the EU are reciprocal, and if the EU took seriously its conviction that more economic integration is desirable, its leaders would seek to ensure that the ties remain as close as possible given the circumstances.
Now, Jean-Claude Juncker, the architect of massive tax avoidance schemes to the benefit of companies in Luxembourg and now President of the European Commission, appears to be taking a tough stance: "Out means out," he declared.
This instinctive reaction may be understandable, given that Juncker could be seen as the one who presided over the first step in the dissolution of the EU.
He argues that, in order to deter other countries from leaving, the EU must accept no concessions, offering the United Kingdom little more than what the WTO agreements guarantee to it.
In other words, the EU should not be kept united by the benefits it offers its members, which far exceed its costs.
Economic prosperity, a sense of solidarity, and the pride of being European are not enough, according to Juncker.
No, the EU must be maintained through threats, intimidation, and fear.
This stance fails to take into account a lesson that is clearly evident, both in the vote in favor of Brexit and in the Republican primaries in the United States: a significant portion of the population has suffered greatly in recent times.
The neoliberal agenda of the past four decades has perhaps been beneficial for the top 1%, but not for the rest of the population.
I had long predicted that this stagnation would eventually have political consequences.
The day has finally arrived.
Citizens on both sides of the Atlantic consider trade agreements to be the source of their troubles.
Although this is an excessive simplification, it is understandable.
Today's trade agreements are negotiated in secret, ensuring good representation of business interests but complete exclusion of ordinary citizens or workers.
The results have been one-way only, with workers' negotiating position weakening further, thus exacerbating the effects of laws that reduce the weight of unions and the rights of employees.
Although trade agreements have played a role in creating these inequalities, many other factors have contributed to tipping the political balance in favor of capital.
Intellectual property rules, for instance, have enhanced the power of pharmaceutical companies to hike prices.
