In many sectors, industrial concentration is on the rise – and so is market power.
The effects of stagnation and real wage decline have been compounded by those of austerity, which has threatened cuts in public services relied upon by many low- and middle-income workers.
The economic uncertainty resulting for workers, when combined with migration, has created a toxic mix.
Many refugees are victims of the wars and oppression to which the West has contributed.
Providing aid is a moral responsibility for all, but especially for the former colonial powers.
And yet, although many might deny it, an increase in unskilled labor supply leads – as long as we are faced with normal negative-sloping demand curves – to a decrease in equilibrium wages.
And when wages cannot fall, unemployment increases.
This is especially worrying in countries where poor economic management has already led to a high level of overall unemployment.
The EU, particularly the eurozone, has been very poorly managed over the past few decades, to the point that its average unemployment rate is now in double digits.
Unrestricted migration in the EU means that countries which have better succeeded in reducing unemployment will inevitably end up hosting more refugees than their fair share.
Workers in these countries bear the cost of depressed wages and higher unemployment, while employers benefit from a cheaper workforce.
The burden of refugees, as expected, is borne by those who are least able to do so.
Of course, there is a lot of talk about the net benefits of immigration.
For a country offering a low level of guaranteed benefits – social protection, education, healthcare, etc. – to all its citizens, this may be the case.
For countries that offer a decent level of social security benefits, the opposite is true.
The result of all this downward pressure on wages and cuts to public services has been the evisceration of the middle class, with similar consequences on both sides of the Atlantic.
Households of the middle class and working class have not benefited from economic growth.
They understand that banks caused the 2008 crisis; but they then saw billions allocated to saving the banks, and insignificant amounts to save their homes and jobs.
While the real median income (adjusted for inflation) for a full-time male worker in the United States is lower than it was four decades ago, voter outrage should come as no surprise.
In addition, politicians who promised change have failed to deliver.
Ordinary citizens knew the system was unfair, but they began to see it as even more rigged than they had imagined, thus losing the little faith they still had in the ability or willingness of traditional politicians to fix it.
This is also understandable: the new politicians shared the perspectives of those who promised that globalization would be beneficial to all.
However, an angry vote does not solve the problems, and may actually lead to a more dismal political and economic situation.
It's the same if one responds with anger to a vote.
Forgetting the past is a basic principle in economics.
From both sides of the Channel, politics must now seek to understand how, in a democracy, the political establishment was able to do so little to address the concerns of many citizens.
Each EU government must now consider improving the well-being of ordinary citizens as its top priority.
More neoliberal ideology won't help.
And we should stop confusing means and ends: for instance, free trade, if well managed, could bring greater shared prosperity; but if poorly managed, it will certainly lower the standard of living of many – perhaps the majority – of citizens.
There are alternatives to current neoliberal measures that can create shared prosperity, just as there are alternatives - such as the Transatlantic Trade and Investment Partnership proposed by US President Barack Obama - that would cause much more harm.
The challenge today is to learn from the past, in order to adopt the first and avoid the second.
